<div id="review_3215535051" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3215535051" />
    <a title="Steve Felt" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/18266870-steve-felt"><img alt="Steve Felt" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1363010697p2/18266870.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3215535051?book_show_action=true">Mar 02, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Steve Felt" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Steve Felt" href="/user/show/18266870-steve-felt">Steve Felt</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3215535051" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7620121062500164628">I love this book. Yes it is cyberpunk, yes it is a near future sort of post apocalyptic, yes it is a crime mystery thriller, but mostly it is about life and how we put our stories together, seemingly rationally and instinctually at the same time, about how life is planned and how shit happens, and about what we have and what we have lost. It does all this by using the Bridge community to help the readers (us) examine our lives in fresh ways.</span>

          </span>
        </div>


