<span id="freeTextContainer536289438089119435"><i>Librarian Note: There is more than one author in the Goodreads database with this name. <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/topic/show_group/44217.Master_List_of_Author_Disambiguation_by_Spaces' rel='nofollow noopener'>See this thread for more information.</a></i><br/><br/>William Ford Gibson is an American-Canadian writer who has been called the father of the cyberpunk subgenre of science fiction, having coined the term <i>cyberspace</i> in 1982 and popularized it in his first novel, <i>Neuromancer</i>(1984), which has sold more than 6.5 million copies wor</span>
  <span id="freeText536289438089119435" style="display:none"><i>Librarian Note: There is more than one author in the Goodreads database with this name. <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/topic/show_group/44217.Master_List_of_Author_Disambiguation_by_Spaces" rel="nofollow noopener">See this thread for more information.</a></i><br /><br />William Ford Gibson is an American-Canadian writer who has been called the father of the cyberpunk subgenre of science fiction, having coined the term <i>cyberspace</i> in 1982 and popularized it in his first novel, <i>Neuromancer</i>(1984), which has sold more than 6.5 million copies worldwide.<br /><br />While his early writing took the form of short stories, Gibson has since written nine critically acclaimed novels (one in collaboration), contributed articles to several major publications, and has collaborated extensively with performance artists, filmmakers and musicians. His thought has been cited as an influence on science fiction authors, academia, cyberculture, and technology.<br /><br /><br />---------------------------------<br /><br /><i>William Gibson. (2007, October 17). In Wikipedia, The Free Encyclopedia. Retrieved 20:30, October 19, 2007, from <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=William_Gibson&amp;oldid=165254323">http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?t...</a></i></span>
